{{Infobox book | name =Reflections on Violence | title_orig ={{lang|fr|Réflexions sur la violence}} | translator = | image =Reflections on Violence.jpg | caption = | author =[[Georges Sorel]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country =France | language =French | subject = | genre = | release_date =1908–1912 | english_release_date = | media_type = | preceded_by =The Decomposition of Marxism | followed_by = }} {{Fin de siecle sidebar}} '''''Reflections on Violence''''' ({{lang-fr|Réflexions sur la violence|links=no}}), published in 1908, is a book by the French revolutionary [[Syndicalism|syndicalist]] [[Georges Sorel]] on [[Class conflict|class struggle]] and [[revolution]].<ref>{{cite book|first1=Marvin|last1=Perry|first2=Matthew|last2=Berg|first3=James|last3=Krukones|title=Sources of Twentieth-Century Europe|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|year=2000|page=46}}</ref> Sorel is known for his theory that political revolution depends on the [[proletariat]] organizing violent [[uprising]]s and [[general strike|strikes]] to institute [[syndicalism]],<ref name=Jennings>{{cite book|editor-first=Jeremy|editor-last=Jennings|chapter=Reflections on violence|first=Georges|last=Sorel|title=Cambridge Texts of the History of Political Thought|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1999|pages=ix−xxi}}</ref> an [[economic system]] in which ''{{lang|fr|[[syndicate|syndicats]]}}'' (self-organizing groups of only proletarians) truly represent the needs of the working class.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Jennings|first1=Jeremy|title=Revolution and the Republic: A History of Political Thought in France Since the Eighteenth Century|date=2011|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=9780198203131|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G5_tdrlGPOQC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA420#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=420}}</ref>
One of Sorel's most controversial claims was that violence could save the world from "[[barbarian|barbarism]]".<ref name=Jennings/> He equated violence with life, creativity, and virtue.<ref name=Jennings/>
In this book, he contends that [[myth]]s are important as "expressions of will to act".<ref name=Jennings/> He also supports the creation of an economic system run by and for the interests of [[Production (economics)|producers]] rather than [[Consumption (economics)|consumers]].<ref name=Jennings/> His ideas were influenced by various other philosophical writers, including [[Giambattista Vico]], [[Blaise Pascal]], [[Ernest Renan]], [[Friedrich Nietzsche]], [[Eduard von Hartmann]], [[Pierre-Joseph Proudhon]], [[John Henry Newman]], [[Karl Marx]], and [[Alexis de Tocqueville]].<ref name=Jennings/>
