{{Infobox company | name = SwoopThat, LLC. | type = [[Privately held company|Private]] |foundation = 2009 | location = [[San Diego]], California, USA | key_people = Jonathan Simkin (CEO), Kevin King (CTO), Benjamin Carson (COO) | industry = [[Price comparison service]], online [[textbook]] price comparison | homepage = }}
'''SwoopThat.com''' was an online [[textbook]] [[price comparison service]]. It was based in [[San Diego]], [[California]], it specialized in [[college]] textbooks but includes [[high school]] textbooks as well. The company's [[books by course]] [[search engine]] lets students input their class schedules, see all the required textbooks for those schedules, and find the cheapest online sources of those books.<ref>{{cite web | last = Komando | first = Kim | title = Save money on textbooks. | publisher = The Kim Komando Show | url = http://www.komando.com/coolsites/index.aspx?id=10044 | date = 2011-01-04 }}</ref> The search engine also includes a [[textbook exchange]] feature through which students can buy and sell books from other students.<ref>{{cite web | last = Bernard | first = Tara Siegel | title = The Bucks Guide to Finding Cheap Textbooks: 3rd Edition. | publisher = The New York Times | url = http://bucks.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/08/23/the-bucks-guide-to-finding-cheap-textbooks-3rd-edition/ | date = 2011-08-23 }}</ref> The website also includes a textbook buyback platform through which students can sell their textbooks back to online vendors. SwoopThat has been featured in the ''[[New York Times]]'', on the website of the ''[[Today (NBC program)|Today Show]]'',<ref>{{cite web | last = Coffey | first = Laura T | title = 11 ways to beat the system when buying college textbooks. | publisher = Today.com | url = http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/26161407/ns/today-back_to_school/t/ways-beat-system-when-buying-college-textbooks/#.TlbT3agxZnA | date = 2011-08-25 }}</ref> on the website of ''[[Computerworld]]'' magazine,<ref>{{cite web | last = Mitchell | first = Robert L | title = Swoopthat scoops up college textbook bargains. | publisher = computerworld | url = http://blogs.computerworld.com/18783/swoopthat_digs_for_college_text_book_savings | date = 2011-08-11 }}</ref> and the [[weblog]] [[lifehacker.com]].
==History and business model== SwoopThat was founded by students from [[Claremont McKenna College]] and [[Harvey Mudd College]]. It originally existed as a product search engine with an emphasis on local products and stores.<ref>{{cite web | last = Fitzpatrick | first = Jason | title = SwoopThat Compares Online and Local Merchant Prices. | publisher = lifehacker.com | url = http://lifehacker.com/#!5670682/swoopthat-compares-local-and-online-merchant-prices/ | date = 2010-10-22 }}</ref> It later shifted to a focus on [[textbooks]] based on a [[books by course]] model. It has since added course and textbook data from over 2,300 colleges in the United States. Through SwoopThat, students can compare prices for new books, [[used books]], rental books, and [[ebooks]].<ref>{{cite web | last = Podplesky | first = Azaria | title = SwoopThat: Website saves average student 50 percent on textbook costs. | publisher = The Easterner | url = http://www.easterneronline.com/news/swoopthat-website-saves-average-student-50-percent-on-textbook-costs-1.2144290/ | date = 2011-04-06 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Laird | first = Brittany | title = New site seeks to help students. | publisher = The Liberty Champion | url = http://www.libertychampion.com/2011/04/12/new-site-seeks-to-help-students/#high_2/ | date = 2011-04-12 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Ramanujam | first = Akshaya | title = Bookstore rental program continues successfully. | publisher = The California Aggie | url = http://theaggie.org/article/2011/04/12/bookstore-rental-program-continues-successfully }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Miller | first = Dan | title = "Back to School"= More Shopping Mashups. | publisher = OpusResearch | url = http://opusresearch.net/wordpress/2010/09/07/back-to-school-more-shopping-mashups// | date = 2010-09-07 }}</ref>
